23:50

Animations are done in Blockbuster Mod, very powerful tool. 

[DISCLAIMER] Various events shown in this video may have been re-arranged, exaggerated, or fabricated for entertainment value or ease of story telling. More info:
- You may notice in some parts it says "2/~300" people sleeping, which implies that the server does not in fact have 1000 people. Its misleading; the way our server software, Multipaper, manages 1000 people is by splitting up the world into multiple threads (or basically, multiple different worlds all synchronously stitched into one). I should also mention that we weren't able to get a constant stream of 1,000 players, as many players rage quitted or had to leave early- we can't control things like this.
- This really experimental software had issues, some of the base got rolled back so worldedit was used to correct for it. The Pros worked incredibly hard and the worldedit was simply done to reverse their work. There were also many technical issues that happened, and I apologize to any player in this event who had it get in their way. 
- The actual battle was 30 mins. Nothing happened then, so I extended it, so I can have interesting things happen.
- We actually had a bit more than 10 players, and for good reason; for example, Coldified was caught xraying on the resource world and we had to ban him, and so having a few extra players helped in times like those.

Believe it or not I was actually biasing the event to have the outcome be the opposite of what ended up happening, I just underestimated how good the winning party was :)

snippet.description:
The survival action series "Alice in Borderland" became the most watched Japanese Netflix title by worldwide audiences.

Their memories of the borderland were erased, but they see glimpses of it in dreams and hallucinations. One day, Usagi, led by afterlife researcher Ryuji (#KentoKaku), suddenly vanishes. At the same time as Usagi's disappearance, Banda (#HayatoIsomura) hands Arisu the final card: the Joker.

What is Roblox? ROBLOX is an online virtual playground and workshop, where kids of all ages can safely interact, create, have fun, and learn. It’s unique in that practically everything on ROBLOX is designed and constructed by members of the community. ROBLOX is designed for 13 to 18 year olds, but it is open to people of all ages. Each player starts by choosing an avatar and giving it an identity. They can then explore ROBLOX — interacting with others by chatting, playing games, or collaborating on creative projects. Each player is also given their own piece of undeveloped real estate along with a virtual toolbox with which to design and build anything — be it a navigable skyscraper, a working helicopter, a giant pinball machine, a multiplayer “Capture the Flag” game or some other, yet-to-be-dreamed-up creation. There is no cost for this first plot of virtual land. By participating and by building cool stuff, ROBLOX members can earn specialty badges as well as ROBLOX dollars (“Robux”). In turn, they can shop the online catalog to purchase avatar clothing and accessories as well as premium building materials, interactive components, and working mechanisms.
